  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering, both at the national and international levels. In the United States, the primary statute is the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** of 1970, as amended by the **USA PATRIOT Act** and other laws. The BSA requires financial institutions to report suspicious activities and maintain records to combat money laundering. Additionally, the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** made money laundering a federal crime, with provisions under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957** addressing specific money laundering offenses.\n\nGlobally, the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have implemented FATF recommendations into their domestic laws. For example:\n\n- In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** provide a framework for member states.\n- In the **United Kingdom**, the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** (POCA) is the primary legislation.\n- In **Canada**, the **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act** addresses these issues.\n\nThese statutes typically criminalize the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, often by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems. Penalties for money laundering can include imprisonment, fines, and asset forfeiture.",
